    chapters: [
      {
        id: "refraction",
        title: "Refraction & Lenses",
        notes: `Refraction is the bending of light as it passes from one transparent medium to another with a different optical density.

### Snell's Law:
$$n_1 \\sin\\theta_1 = n_2 \\sin\\theta_2$$
Where $n = c/v$ is the refractive index of the medium.

### Total Internal Reflection:
When light travels from a denser medium to a rarer medium ($n_1 > n_2$) at an angle greater than the critical angle $\\theta_c$:
$$\\sin\\theta_c = \\frac{n_2}{n_1}$$

### Thin Lens Formulas:
- **Lens Formula:** $$\\frac{1}{f} = \\frac{1}{v} - \\frac{1}{u}$$
- **Lens Maker's Equation:** $$\\frac{1}{f} = \\left(\\frac{n_{\\text{lens}}}{n_{\\text{medium}}} - 1\\right)\\left(\\frac{1}{R_1} - \\frac{1}{R_2}\\right)$$
- **Magnification:** $$m = \\frac{h_i}{h_o} = \\frac{v}{u}$$`,
        formulas: [
          { name: "Snell's Law", latex: "n_1 \\sin\\theta_1 = n_2 \\sin\\theta_2", explanation: "Relates angles of incidence and refraction to refractive indices" },
          { name: "Critical Angle", latex: "\\sin\\theta_c = n_2 / n_1", explanation: "Angle of incidence that results in a 90-degree refraction angle" },
          { name: "Thin Lens Equation", latex: "1/f = 1/v - 1/u", explanation: "f: focal length, v: image distance, u: object distance (Cartesian signs)" }
        ],
        flashcards: [
          { id: "op-r1", question: "What is total internal reflection, and when does it occur?", answer: "It is the complete reflection of a light ray inside an optically denser medium. It occurs when light hits the boundary of a less dense medium at an angle of incidence greater than the critical angle." }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
